# Fluff Date: 2026-02-19 16:29:24
overview:<p>The Scavenger is an eighty-ton quadruped IndustrialMech introduced in 2613 by Bristol SalvageWorks on Canopus IV, designed to recover damaged and destroyed BattleMechs and other combat equipment from the battlefield. Purpose-built for the Magistracy of Canopus and its Canopian Salvage Corps, the Scavenger filled a critical support role that most Inner Sphere militaries considered beneath their attention. Unable to replace combat losses at the rate of the Great Houses, the Magistracy instead perfected the art of battlefield recovery, and the Scavenger became the Corps' primary tool for reclaiming everything from intact weapons and armor plating to liquid coolants and functional engine cores.</p><p>Powered by a fuel cell engine, the design prioritized cargo capacity and operational endurance over speed or combat capability, reflecting the Periphery realm's pragmatic approach to stretching limited military resources as far as possible.</p>

capabilities:<p>The Scavenger's design centers entirely on its salvage recovery mission, eschewing any combat capability in favor of maximum utility. Its 320-rated fuel cell engine provides a respectable top speed of sixty-four kilometers per hour for an eighty-ton machine, allowing salvage teams to reach battlefield sites before rival scavengers or hostile forces can secure the wreckage. An extended three-ton fuel tank gives the Scavenger the operational range needed for multi-day recovery missions across large battlefields, a critical advantage when cleanup operations can stretch on for weeks.</p><p>The 'Mech's primary tools are its fluid suction system and sprayer, which allow crews to drain and collect liquid salvage including coolants, petroleum fuels, and oils from wrecked machines. A searchlight assists operations in low-visibility conditions or inside damaged structures. The Scavenger carries a twelve-ton cargo bay for solid salvage and two tons of liquid storage for recovered fluids. While this capacity is substantial, Corps teams routinely require multiple sorties to fully strip a large battlefield.</p><p>The Scavenger mounts no weapons or targeting systems and relies entirely on industrial-grade armor for protection, making it wholly dependent on escort forces when operating in contested areas. Its quadruped configuration provides superior stability when hauling heavy loads across uneven terrain.</p>

deployment:<p>Introduced around 2990 during the depths of the Succession Wars, the SC-V-M strips out all salvage equipment, cargo bays, and fluid handling systems from the base Scavenger chassis. In their place, the MilitiaMech mounts a single autocannon/10 with two tons of ammunition, backed by an advanced fire control system to compensate for the IndustrialMech's rudimentary sensors. An additional heat sink manages the thermal load from sustained firing. The conversion reflects the Magistracy's pragmatic willingness to arm any available chassis during the desperate military shortages of the late Succession Wars, providing planetary militias with a crude but functional eighty-ton fire support platform. The searchlight is retained for patrol operations.</p>

history:<p>The Scavenger's history is inextricably linked to the Magistracy of Canopus and its Canopian Salvage Corps, one of the most underappreciated military support organizations in the Inner Sphere. Bristol SalvageWorks introduced the design in 2613, during the height of the Star League era, when the Magistracy first formalized its approach to battlefield recovery. While the Great Houses could afford to leave damaged equipment on the field and replace it from massive industrial bases, the Periphery realm had no such luxury, and the Salvage Corps became an essential element of the Magistracy Armed Forces' logistics chain.</p><p>The Scavenger served throughout the Succession Wars as the Corps' primary recovery vehicle, its simple fuel cell engine and rugged construction proving remarkably durable in the face of declining technical capability across the Inner Sphere. During this era, the design also found operators beyond the Magistracy. The Gray Death Legion, one of the most storied mercenary commands of the thirty-first century, was among the noted users of the Scavenger, demonstrating that even elite units recognized the value of dedicated salvage assets in an age of irreplaceable technology.</p><p>The desperate military conditions of the late Succession Wars prompted the introduction of the SC-V-M MilitiaMech variant around 2990, converting the salvage platform into a crude combat vehicle for planetary defense. While a poor substitute for a true BattleMech, the MilitiaMech provided under-equipped garrisons with an eighty-ton platform mounting an autocannon and fire control system, capable of at least discouraging raider attacks against worlds that might otherwise be defenseless.</p><p>The Scavenger's long service ultimately led to its evolution into the upgraded SC-V-1 Vampyr in 3066, which incorporated Trinity Alliance technologies including industrial triple strength myomer and environmental sealing. However, the base Scavenger remained in use with numerous operators who either could not afford or did not require the Vampyr's enhanced capabilities, ensuring the venerable design continued to see service well into the thirty-second century.</p>

